<CaseStudy slug="cs-prompt-field-kit">
  <p class="lead reveal">A prompt library is easy to ship and easy to ignore. People copy a line, it does not quite fit their situation, and they quietly go back to writing from scratch. So I built a field kit instead: prompts for real customer-success jobs, each one taken apart so the person using it learns the shape and can adapt it, not just paste it.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">Every card is a teardown</h2>
  <p class="reveal">The kit is 18 cards, one per CS job to be done: the at-risk save play, the mutual success plan, the reference request, the churn post-mortem, and more. Each card breaks its prompt into five moving parts, so you can see which lever does what and swap any one of them for your own account. It reads like a worked example, not a vending machine.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">Built to be used on the job</h2>
  <p class="reveal">You filter by the job you are actually doing, copy the prompt in one click, and go. It is a static site, so it loads instantly and works on a phone between calls. There is a short rollout page too, tying the kit to a wider adoption story rather than leaving it as a pile of tips.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">Held to a real bar</h2>
  <p class="reveal">A build-time gate refuses to ship a card that is missing any of its five elements, so the quality bar is mechanical, not a matter of me remembering. The teardowns use plausible, non-strawman bad examples, because a teardown that only mocks an obviously terrible prompt teaches nothing.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">Why I point to this one</h2>
  <p class="reveal">Enablement is teaching, and teaching means showing your work. This kit is what I would hand a CS team on day one: not "here are some prompts," but "here is how a good prompt is built, for the exact jobs you have, so you can make your own."</p>
</CaseStudy>
